  "english_translation": {
    "entry_translation": "Sūrat Āl ʿImrān.\n\nMedinan. It has no counterpart (naẓīrah) in its verse-count. Its words are three thousand four hundred and eighty, and its letters are fourteen thousand five hundred and twenty-five. It is two hundred verses in all systems of counting.\n\nIts points of disagreement are seven verse-endings: “Alif Lām Mīm” is counted by the Kufi and not by the others; the first occurrence of “al-Injīl” is not counted by the Shami, while the others count it; “wa-anzala al-furqān” is not counted by the Kufi, while the others count it; the second occurrence of “al-Injīl” is counted by the Kufi and not by the others—and they all omit “al-Injīl” in al-Māʾida, al-Aʿrāf, and al-Fatḥ; “wa-rasūlan ilā banī isrāʾīl” is counted by the Basri and not by the others; “kāna ḥillan li-banī isrāʾīl” is not counted by any of them; and the first occurrence of “mimmā tuḥibbūn” is not counted by the Kufi, the Basri, or Abū Jaʿfar al-Qāriʾ, while the others and Shayba b. Niṣāḥ count it.\n\nIn it there are nine places that resemble verse-endings without being counted, by consensus: “lahum ʿadhābun shadīd”; “inna al-dīna ʿinda Allāhi al-islām”; “fī al-ummiyyīna sabīl”; “a-fa-ghayra dīni Allāhi yabghūn”; “ulāʾika lahum ʿadhābun alīm”; “man istaṭāʿa ilayhi sabīlan”; “min baʿdi mā arākum mā tuḥibbūn”; “yawma iltaqā al-jamʿān”; and “matāʿun qalīl.”",
    "ruus_translation_note": "The running رؤوس الآي are represented here as an ordered Arabic sequence on the المدني الأخير baseline. The local text witness required minor editorial normalization: one compressed pair was split (مما تحبون / به عليم), one head appears as an unnumbered line (ذو انتقام), and the page-break numerals for 140 and the final total were repaired from sequence and a checked parallel witness."
  },
